{"id":879,"date":"2023-03-14T07:08:34","date_gmt":"2023-03-14T07:08:34","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/?p=879"},"modified":"2023-04-04T10:30:09","modified_gmt":"2023-04-04T10:30:09","slug":"16-ui-design-rules","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/blog\/ui-design\/16-ui-design-rules","title":{"rendered":"16 little UI design rules that make a big impact"},"content":{"rendered":"\n<p>User interface design is hard. With so many options to choose from regarding layout, spacing, typography, and colour, making design decisions can be overwhelming. When you add usability, accessibility, and psychology to the mix, it gets even harder.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Luckily, UI design doesn\u2019t have to be so hard. Over nearly 2 decades working as a product designer, I\u2019ve realised that most of my visual and interaction design decisions are governed by a system of logical rules. Not artistic flair or magical intuition, just simple rules.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Having a system of logical rules helps you efficiently make informed design decisions. Without a logical system, you\u2019re just using gut feeling to move stuff around until it looks pretty.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>I love rules and logic, but design decisions are rarely black and white. Rather than strict rules that you must follow, think of the following advice as helpful guidelines that work well in most cases.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>The quickest way to learn is by doing, so let\u2019s get started.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"\/>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Let\u2019s fix this example using logical&nbsp;rules<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>The following 2 designs are for the property details page of a short-term property rental app. The first one is the original design. The second is the result of applying some logical rules or guidelines.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1880\" height=\"2000\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-0-1880x2000.jpg\" alt=\"UI design example before and after\" class=\"wp-image-880\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-0-1880x2000.jpg 1880w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-0-282x300.jpg 282w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-0-768x817.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-0-1444x1536.jpg 1444w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-0-1925x2048.jpg 1925w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1880px) 100vw, 1880px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Even without much visual or interaction design experience, you\u2019ll probably notice that the original design feels messy, complicated, and difficult to use. This is because it contains many problematic design details that pose a risk to usability. Perhaps you can already spot a few?<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Let\u2019s fix the problems with the original design one at a time using the following logical rules or guidelines:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<ol>\n<li><a href=\"#1\">Use space to group related elements<\/a><\/li>\n\n\n\n<li><a href=\"#2\">Be consistent<\/a><\/li>\n\n\n\n<li><a href=\"#3\">Ensure similar looking elements function similarly<\/a><\/li>\n\n\n\n<li><a href=\"#4\">Create a clear visual hierarchy<\/a><\/li>\n\n\n\n<li><a href=\"#5\">Remove unnecessary styles<\/a><\/li>\n\n\n\n<li><a href=\"#6\">Use colour purposefully<\/a><\/li>\n\n\n\n<li><a href=\"#7\">Ensure interface elements have a 3:1 contrast ratio<\/a><\/li>\n\n\n\n<li><a href=\"#8\">Ensure text has a 4.5:1 contrast ratio<\/a><\/li>\n\n\n\n<li><a href=\"#9\">Don\u2019t rely on colour alone as an indicator<\/a><\/li>\n\n\n\n<li><a href=\"#10\">Use a single sans serif typeface<\/a><\/li>\n\n\n\n<li><a href=\"#11\">Use a typeface with taller lower case letters<\/a><\/li>\n\n\n\n<li><a href=\"#12\">Limit the use of uppercase<\/a><\/li>\n\n\n\n<li><a href=\"#13\">Use regular and bold font weights only<\/a><\/li>\n\n\n\n<li><a href=\"#14\">Avoid pure black text<\/a><\/li>\n\n\n\n<li><a href=\"#15\">Left align text<\/a><\/li>\n\n\n\n<li><a href=\"#16\">Use at least 1.5 line height for body text<\/a><\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n\n\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"\/>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"1\">1. Use space to group related&nbsp;elements<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>Breaking up information into smaller groups of related elements helps to structure and organise an interface. This makes it faster and easier for people to understand and remember.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>You can group related elements using the following methods:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<ol>\n<li>Place related elements in the same container<\/li>\n\n\n\n<li>Space related elements close together<\/li>\n\n\n\n<li>Make related elements look similar<\/li>\n\n\n\n<li>Align related elements in a continuous line<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n\n\n<p>Using containers is the strongest visual cue to group interface elements, but it can add unnecessary clutter. Look for opportunities to use other grouping methods, they\u2019re often more subtle and can help simplify designs.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Using space in particular is a very effective and simple way to group related elements. You can also combine grouping methods to help display groupings more clearly.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In our example, the lack of space between content makes the design look cluttered and difficult to understand. Increasing spacing helps to clearly group content, making it more organised and easier to understand.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1880\" height=\"2000\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-1-1880x2000.jpg\" alt=\"User interface example without sufficient spacing vs one with sufficient spacing\" class=\"wp-image-881\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-1-1880x2000.jpg 1880w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-1-282x300.jpg 282w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-1-768x817.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-1-1444x1536.jpg 1444w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-1-1925x2048.jpg 1925w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1880px) 100vw, 1880px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"2\">2. Be consistent<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>Consistency in UI design means that similar elements look and work in a similar way. This should be true both within your product and when compared with other well-established products. This predictable functionality improves usability and reduces errors, as people don\u2019t need to keep learning how things work.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In our example, the icon styles are inconsistent, as some are filled and others aren\u2019t. This could confuse some people, as filled icons often indicate that an element is selected. Outlining all icons with a 2pt stroke weight and rounded corners improves consistency and gives each icon a similar visual weight.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"2000\" height=\"978\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-2.1-2000x978.jpg\" alt=\"Inconsistently styled icons vs consistently styled icons\" class=\"wp-image-882\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-2.1-2000x978.jpg 2000w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-2.1-300x147.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-2.1-768x376.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-2.1-1536x751.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-2.1-2048x1002.jpg 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2000px) 100vw, 2000px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Text labels are also added to the icons to help ensure people can understand what they mean, especially those using screen readers (software that describes an interface, using speech or braille, to someone who can\u2019t see it).<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1880\" height=\"2000\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-2-1880x2000.jpg\" alt=\"UI design example with inconsistent icon styles vs one with consistent icons styles\" class=\"wp-image-883\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-2-1880x2000.jpg 1880w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-2-282x300.jpg 282w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-2-768x817.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-2-1444x1536.jpg 1444w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-2-1925x2048.jpg 1925w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1880px) 100vw, 1880px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"3\">3. Ensure similar looking elements function similarly<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>If elements look similar, people will expect them to work in a similar way. So try to ensure that you use a consistent visual treatment for elements with the same functionality. Conversely, try to ensure elements with different functionality look different.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In our example, the icon containers have a similar visual style to the \u201cbook now\u201d button. This makes them seem interactive, even though they\u2019re not. Removing the blue colour and button styling from the icons helps to avoid them being mistaken for interactive elements.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1880\" height=\"2000\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-3-1880x2000.jpg\" alt=\"Updated UI design example that ensures similar looking elements function similarly\" class=\"wp-image-884\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-3-1880x2000.jpg 1880w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-3-282x300.jpg 282w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-3-768x817.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-3-1444x1536.jpg 1444w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-3-1925x2048.jpg 1925w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1880px) 100vw, 1880px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"4\">4. Create a clear visual hierarchy<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>Not all information in an interface has the same level of importance. Aim to present information in order of importance by making more important elements look more prominent.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>A clear order of importance, or visual hierarchy, helps people scan information quickly and focus on areas of interest. It also improves aesthetics by creating a sense of order. You can create a clear visual hierarchy using variations in size, colour, contrast, spacing, position, and depth.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Here\u2019s an example of a website hero banner without a clear visual hierarchy, followed by one with elements clearly presented in order of importance.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"2000\" height=\"875\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-4.3-2000x875.jpg\" alt=\"Example of a website hero banner without a clear visual hierarchy\" class=\"wp-image-887\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-4.3-2000x875.jpg 2000w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-4.3-300x131.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-4.3-768x336.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-4.3-1536x672.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-4.3-2048x896.jpg 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2000px) 100vw, 2000px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"2000\" height=\"875\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-4.4-2000x875.jpg\" alt=\"Example of a website hero banner with a clear visual hierarchy\" class=\"wp-image-888\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-4.4-2000x875.jpg 2000w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-4.4-300x131.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-4.4-768x336.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-4.4-1536x672.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-4.4-2048x896.jpg 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2000px) 100vw, 2000px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>A quick and easy way to test whether your visual hierarchy is clear is to use The Squint Test. Simply squint your eyes and look at your design. Alternatively you can move further away from the screen or blur your design. You should still be able to tell what the most important elements are and recognise what the interface is for.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Let\u2019s apply the Squint Test to our example. We can see that there are multiple elements with similarly strong prominence competing for attention. Meanwhile, the primary action in the bottom left doesn\u2019t stand out at all.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"2000\" height=\"1923\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-4.1-2000x1923.jpg\" alt=\"Applying the Squint test to the example\" class=\"wp-image-885\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-4.1-2000x1923.jpg 2000w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-4.1-300x289.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-4.1-768x739.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-4.1-1536x1477.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-4.1-2048x1970.jpg 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2000px) 100vw, 2000px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The primary action should generally be the most prominent element on an interface. Giving it a high contrast background colour and bold font weight helps achieve this. This also fixes an accessibility issue with the low contrast button, which we\u2019ll look into later.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1880\" height=\"2000\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-4-1880x2000.jpg\" alt=\"Giving the primary action  a high contrast background colour and bold font weight to make it the most prominent element\" class=\"wp-image-889\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-4-1880x2000.jpg 1880w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-4-282x300.jpg 282w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-4-768x817.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-4-1444x1536.jpg 1444w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-4-1925x2048.jpg 1925w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1880px) 100vw, 1880px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Applying the Squint Test to the updated design, the primary action is clearly the most prominent element.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"2000\" height=\"1923\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-4.2-2000x1923.jpg\" alt=\"Applying the Squint Test to the updated design, the primary action is clearly the most prominent element.\" class=\"wp-image-886\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-4.2-2000x1923.jpg 2000w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-4.2-300x289.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-4.2-768x739.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-4.2-1536x1477.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-4.2-2048x1970.jpg 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2000px) 100vw, 2000px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The visual hierarchy is now clearer, but there\u2019s still room for improvement. For example, the block of body text is still too prominent relative to its level of importance. We\u2019ll learn some quick typography guidelines shortly, which will help correct the visual hierarchy.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"5\">5. Remove unnecessary styles<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>Unnecessary information and visual styles can be distracting and can increase cognitive load (the amount of brain power required to use an interface). Avoid unnecessary lines, colours, backgrounds, and animations to create a simpler, more focused interface.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"2000\" height=\"1095\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-5.1-2000x1095.jpg\" alt=\"Unnecessary white space and borders are removed to simplify the design\" class=\"wp-image-890\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-5.1-2000x1095.jpg 2000w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-5.1-300x164.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-5.1-768x420.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-5.1-1536x841.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-5.1-2048x1121.jpg 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2000px) 100vw, 2000px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>In our example, the white space and borders around the image add unnecessary visual complexity. They\u2019re not needed to convey information or group elements, so we can safely remove them to simplify the design.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1880\" height=\"2000\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-5-1880x2000.jpg\" alt=\"Unnecessary white space and borders are removed to simplify the design\" class=\"wp-image-891\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-5-1880x2000.jpg 1880w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-5-282x300.jpg 282w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-5-768x817.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-5-1444x1536.jpg 1444w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-5-1925x2048.jpg 1925w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1880px) 100vw, 1880px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"6\">6. Use colour purposefully<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>Use colour sparingly and with purpose. Try to avoid using colour purely for decoration, as it can be confusing and distracting. Start with black and white and introduce colour where it conveys meaning.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>A simple and effective approach is to apply the brand colour to interactive elements like text links and buttons. This helps teach people what\u2019s interactive and what\u2019s not. Try to avoid using the brand colour on non-interactive elements.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>You don\u2019t need to add colour to all interactive elements, as some already have visual cues that indicate they\u2019re interactive. For example, the cards in the following example still feel interactive, with or without the blue coloured link.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"2000\" height=\"1064\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-6.1-2000x1064.jpg\" alt=\"Card component with a blue underlined link vs one without\" class=\"wp-image-892\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-6.1-2000x1064.jpg 2000w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-6.1-300x160.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-6.1-768x409.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-6.1-1536x817.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-6.1-2048x1089.jpg 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2000px) 100vw, 2000px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>In our original example, the blue heading might look nice, but it makes the text seem interactive. To help avoid confusion, we remove the blue colour from the heading as it\u2019s not interactive.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>We also remove the blue colour from other non-interactive elements like the star rating. This makes it much easier to see what\u2019s interactive and what\u2019s not.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1880\" height=\"2000\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-6-1880x2000.jpg\" alt=\"Removing colour from non interactive elements in the example design\" class=\"wp-image-893\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-6-1880x2000.jpg 1880w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-6-282x300.jpg 282w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-6-768x817.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-6-1444x1536.jpg 1444w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-6-1925x2048.jpg 1925w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1880px) 100vw, 1880px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"7\">7. Ensure interface elements have a 3:1 contrast&nbsp;ratio<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>Contrast is a measure of the difference in perceived brightness between two colours. It\u2019s expressed as a ratio ranging from 1:1 to 21:1. For example, black text on a black background has the lowest 1:1 contrast ratio, whereas black text on a white background has the highest 21:1 ratio. There are many <a href=\"https:\/\/usecontrast.com\/\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" target=\"_blank\">online tools<\/a> to help you measure contrast ratios between different colours.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In order to help ensure people with vision impairments can clearly see interface details, aim to at least meet <a href=\"https:\/\/www.w3.org\/TR\/WCAG21\/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG)<\/a> 2.1 level AA colour contrast requirements. This means user interface elements, like form fields and buttons, need to have at least a 3:1 contrast ratio.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In our example, the arrow icon contrast is too low. Adding a shadow to the icon and a gradient overlay on the top third of the image gives the icon sufficient 3:1 contrast, regardless of the image it sits on.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"2000\" height=\"730\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-7.1-2000x730.jpg\" alt=\"Adding a shadow to the icon and a gradient overlay on the top third of the image to give the icon sufficient 3:1 contrast\" class=\"wp-image-894\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-7.1-2000x730.jpg 2000w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-7.1-300x109.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-7.1-768x280.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-7.1-1536x561.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-7.1-2048x747.jpg 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2000px) 100vw, 2000px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The primary button contrast in the original example was also too low. We fixed it previously when addressing the visual hierarchy, but it\u2019s also worth mentioning here.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"2000\" height=\"730\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-7.2-2000x730.jpg\" alt=\"Increasing primary button contrast to at least 3:1\" class=\"wp-image-895\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-7.2-2000x730.jpg 2000w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-7.2-300x109.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-7.2-768x280.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-7.2-1536x561.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-7.2-2048x747.jpg 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2000px) 100vw, 2000px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The risk with the low contrast button is that people with low vision might not identify it as a button, as they can\u2019t see the button shape. Increasing the button contrast ratio above 3:1 makes the button accessible and also helps correct the visual hierarchy.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Increasing the arrow and button contrast to a ratio above 3:1 gives us the following design. We\u2019re getting there bit by bit, but we\u2019ve still got more issues to fix.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1880\" height=\"2000\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-7-1880x2000.jpg\" alt=\"Example design with arrow and button contrast above a 3:1 ratio\" class=\"wp-image-896\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-7-1880x2000.jpg 1880w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-7-282x300.jpg 282w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-7-768x817.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-7-1444x1536.jpg 1444w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-7-1925x2048.jpg 1925w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1880px) 100vw, 1880px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"8\">8. Ensure text has a 4.5:1 contrast&nbsp;ratio<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>In order to help ensure people with vision impairments can clearly read text, it needs to meet the following WCAG 2.1 level AA contrast requirements:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<ul>\n<li>Small text (18px and under) needs a minimum contrast of 4.5:1.<\/li>\n\n\n\n<li>Large text (above 18px with bold weight or above 24px with regular weight) needs a minimum contrast of 3:1.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n\n\n<p>In our example, the small text in the photo count element has insufficient contrast. We increase the contrast ratio above 4.5:1 by increasing the opacity of the grey container and also adding a text shadow.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"2000\" height=\"931\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-8.1-2000x931.jpg\" alt=\"Opacity of the grey photo count container is increased above 4.5:1\" class=\"wp-image-897\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-8.1-2000x931.jpg 2000w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-8.1-300x140.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-8.1-768x357.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-8.1-1536x715.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-8.1-2048x953.jpg 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2000px) 100vw, 2000px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The contrast of the location text is also too low. The thin font weight makes it even harder to read. Using a darker shade of grey helps make the text more accessible. We\u2019ll make further updates to the text to improve it shortly.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1880\" height=\"2000\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-8-1880x2000.jpg\" alt=\"Example design where the opacity of the grey photo count container is increased above 4.5:1\" class=\"wp-image-898\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-8-1880x2000.jpg 1880w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-8-282x300.jpg 282w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-8-768x817.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-8-1444x1536.jpg 1444w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-8-1925x2048.jpg 1925w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1880px) 100vw, 1880px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"9\">9. Don\u2019t rely on colour alone as an indicator<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>There are many different types of colour blindness and they mainly affect men. Commonly, people who are colour blind have difficulty distinguishing between red and green, but some aren\u2019t able to see any colour at all.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>To ensure an interface is accessible to those who are colour blind, you can\u2019t rely on colour alone to convey meaning or distinguish visual elements. You need to use additional visual cues to differentiate interface elements.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In our example, the colour blue is used on the \u201creviews\u201d text to indicate that it\u2019s a link. If colour is removed, the link text looks the same as other text, so the colour blind can\u2019t tell it\u2019s a link. Underlining the link text clearly differentiates it from other text in the absence of colour.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"2000\" height=\"1642\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-9.1-2000x1642.jpg\" alt=\"Comparison of link text with and without an underline when colour is removed\" class=\"wp-image-899\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-9.1-2000x1642.jpg 2000w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-9.1-300x246.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-9.1-768x631.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-9.1-1536x1261.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-9.1-2048x1682.jpg 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2000px) 100vw, 2000px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"10\">10. Use a single sans serif&nbsp;typeface<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>A typeface is a set of related fonts with a similar style or aesthetic. Helvetica is an example of a typeface. Fonts are variations within a typeface, like weights or sizes. For example, Helvetica bold and Helvetica regular are 2 different fonts within the Helvetica typeface.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>It\u2019s safest to use a single sans serif typeface for interface design, as they\u2019re generally the most legible, neutral, and simple.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In our example, the heading uses a detailed serif typeface that\u2019s a bit difficult to read and could be distracting to some. It also has a personality that might not match some of the photos in this property rental app. Simplifying it using a sans serif typeface can help improve usability and aesthetics.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"2000\" height=\"843\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-10.1-2000x843.jpg\" alt=\"Detailed serif typeface vs simple sans serif typeface\" class=\"wp-image-901\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-10.1-2000x843.jpg 2000w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-10.1-300x126.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-10.1-768x324.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-10.1-1536x647.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-10.1-2048x863.jpg 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2000px) 100vw, 2000px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1880\" height=\"2000\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-10-1880x2000.jpg\" alt=\"Detailed serif typeface in example is updated to a simple sans serif typeface\" class=\"wp-image-902\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-10-1880x2000.jpg 1880w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-10-282x300.jpg 282w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-10-768x817.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-10-1444x1536.jpg 1444w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-10-1925x2048.jpg 1925w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1880px) 100vw, 1880px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"11\">11. Use a typeface with taller lower case&nbsp;letters<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>Look for typefaces with taller lower case letters and greater letter spacing, as they\u2019re generally more legible at small sizes. The height of lowercase letters in a typeface is known as the x-height.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"2000\" height=\"657\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/x-height-comparison-1-2000x657.jpg\" alt=\"Comparing the x-height of Gill Sans and Lato typefaces\" class=\"wp-image-917\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/x-height-comparison-1-2000x657.jpg 2000w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/x-height-comparison-1-300x99.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/x-height-comparison-1-768x252.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/x-height-comparison-1-1536x505.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/x-height-comparison-1-2048x673.jpg 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2000px) 100vw, 2000px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Our example uses the Gill Sans typeface, which has a relatively low x-height. Changing the typeface to one with a larger x-height, like Lato, helps to improve readability.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"2000\" height=\"737\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/x-height-comparison-2-2000x737.jpg\" alt=\"Comparing the x-height of Gill Sans and Lato typefaces in an example paragraph of text\" class=\"wp-image-918\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/x-height-comparison-2-2000x737.jpg 2000w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/x-height-comparison-2-300x111.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/x-height-comparison-2-768x283.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/x-height-comparison-2-1536x566.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/x-height-comparison-2-2048x755.jpg 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2000px) 100vw, 2000px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Here\u2019s what our example looks like after the typeface is updated from Gill Sans to Lato.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1880\" height=\"2000\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-11-1880x2000.jpg\" alt=\"Example text updated from Gill Sans to Lato typeface\" class=\"wp-image-903\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-11-1880x2000.jpg 1880w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-11-282x300.jpg 282w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-11-768x817.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-11-1444x1536.jpg 1444w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-11-1925x2048.jpg 1925w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1880px) 100vw, 1880px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"12\">12. Limit the use of uppercase<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>Unless you\u2019re shouting at people, there aren\u2019t many valid reasons to use uppercase. IT\u2019S LOUD AND DIFFICULT TO READ.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>When you read, you look at the shape of a word, rather than looking at each letter. The shape helps you recognise the word more quickly. Uppercase words all have the same rectangular shape. This forces you to read each letter one by one.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"2000\" height=\"597\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/uppercase-shape-1-2000x597.jpg\" alt=\"The shape of an uppercase vs sentence case word\" class=\"wp-image-914\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/uppercase-shape-1-2000x597.jpg 2000w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/uppercase-shape-1-300x90.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/uppercase-shape-1-768x229.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/uppercase-shape-1-1536x458.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/uppercase-shape-1-2048x611.jpg 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2000px) 100vw, 2000px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>In our example, the location text uses uppercase. Changing it to sentence case, where only the first word and proper nouns (names of people, places or things) are capitalised, helps to improve readability.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"2000\" height=\"843\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/uppercase-shape-2-2000x843.jpg\" alt=\"The shape of an uppercase sentence vs one in sentence case\" class=\"wp-image-915\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/uppercase-shape-2-2000x843.jpg 2000w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/uppercase-shape-2-300x126.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/uppercase-shape-2-768x324.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/uppercase-shape-2-1536x647.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/uppercase-shape-2-2048x863.jpg 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2000px) 100vw, 2000px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1880\" height=\"2000\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-12-1880x2000.jpg\" alt=\"Example text changed from uppercase to sentence case\" class=\"wp-image-904\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-12-1880x2000.jpg 1880w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-12-282x300.jpg 282w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-12-768x817.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-12-1444x1536.jpg 1444w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-12-1925x2048.jpg 1925w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1880px) 100vw, 1880px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"13\">13. Use regular and bold font weights&nbsp;only<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>Just because there are lots of font weights available in a typeface, doesn\u2019t mean you need to use all of them in your designs. Using lots of different font weights can add noise and clutter to your interface. It also makes it more difficult to use each font weight consistently.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Keep your design system simple and concise by using regular and bold font weights only.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"2000\" height=\"1438\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-13.2-2000x1438.jpg\" alt=\"Examples of thin, light, regular, semi-bold, and bold fonts with all of them crossed out except for regular and bold\" class=\"wp-image-906\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-13.2-2000x1438.jpg 2000w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-13.2-300x216.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-13.2-768x552.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-13.2-1536x1104.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-13.2-2048x1472.jpg 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2000px) 100vw, 2000px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Quick usage tips:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<ul>\n<li>Use bold font weight for headings to emphasise them.<\/li>\n\n\n\n<li>Use regular font weight for other smaller text.<\/li>\n\n\n\n<li>If you decide to use very thin or thick font weights, reserve them for headings and larger text, as they can be difficult to read at smaller sizes.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n\n\n<p>In our example, the location text uses a light font weight. Even though we\u2019ve increased the contrast above the required 4.5:1 contrast ratio, the thin characters could still be difficult for some people to read. Increasing the font weight to regular helps improve readability and simplifies the design.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"2000\" height=\"843\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-13.1-2000x843.jpg\" alt=\"Location text in light font weight vs regular font weight\" class=\"wp-image-905\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-13.1-2000x843.jpg 2000w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-13.1-300x126.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-13.1-768x324.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-13.1-1536x647.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-13.1-2048x863.jpg 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2000px) 100vw, 2000px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1880\" height=\"2000\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-13-1880x2000.jpg\" alt=\"Example with location text in light font weight vs regular font weight\" class=\"wp-image-907\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-13-1880x2000.jpg 1880w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-13-282x300.jpg 282w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-13-768x817.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-13-1444x1536.jpg 1444w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-13-1925x2048.jpg 1925w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1880px) 100vw, 1880px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"14\">14. Avoid pure black&nbsp;text<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>For UI design, it\u2019s generally safest to avoid pure black, as it has a very high contrast against white. This high contrast can cause eye strain and fatigue when reading text.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Black has 0% colour brightness and white has 100% colour brightness. The large difference in colour brightness causes our eyes to work harder. It\u2019s safest to avoid pure black against white and opt for a dark grey instead.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In our example, pure black is used on multiple elements. Changing it to a dark grey helps to improve readability. Previously when looking at visual hierarchy, we noted that the property description text was too prominent. To make sure interface elements are presented in order of importance, we use a lighter grey for the property description text to decrease its prominence.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1880\" height=\"2000\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-14-1880x2000.jpg\" alt=\"Black text in the example is changed to dark grey\" class=\"wp-image-908\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-14-1880x2000.jpg 1880w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-14-282x300.jpg 282w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-14-768x817.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-14-1444x1536.jpg 1444w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-14-1925x2048.jpg 1925w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1880px) 100vw, 1880px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"15\">15. Left align&nbsp;text<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>English is read from left to right, downwards in an F-shaped pattern. So it\u2019s best to keep text left aligned for optimal readability. For long body text, it\u2019s safest to avoid centre aligned or justified text. It\u2019s more difficult to read, especially for those with cognitive disabilities.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Centre alignment can work for headings and short text, as it can be quickly read. However, centre alignment makes longer body text harder to read, because the starting point of each line constantly changes. Your eyes need to work harder to find the starting point of each line.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"2000\" height=\"1208\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-15.1-2000x1208.jpg\" alt=\"An example of centre aligned text vs left aligned text\" class=\"wp-image-909\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-15.1-2000x1208.jpg 2000w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-15.1-300x181.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-15.1-768x464.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-15.1-1536x928.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-15.1-2048x1237.jpg 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2000px) 100vw, 2000px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>In our example, the property description text is centre aligned. Left aligning the text improves readability and is also consistent with the left aligned text above.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1880\" height=\"2000\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-15-1880x2000.jpg\" alt=\"In our example, the property description text is changed from centre aligned to left aligned.\" class=\"wp-image-910\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-15-1880x2000.jpg 1880w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-15-282x300.jpg 282w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-15-768x817.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-15-1444x1536.jpg 1444w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-15-1925x2048.jpg 1925w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1880px) 100vw, 1880px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"16\">16. Use at least 1.5 line height for body&nbsp;text<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>Line height is the vertical distance between two lines of text. The space between lines helps prevent people from rereading the same line of text. It also looks and feels more comfortable to read.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>For accessibility and readability, especially for long body text, ensure that line height is at least 1.5 (150%). Keeping line height between 1.5 and 2 generally works well.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"2000\" height=\"766\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-16.1-2000x766.jpg\" alt=\"Diagram showing the difference between font size and line height\" class=\"wp-image-911\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-16.1-2000x766.jpg 2000w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-16.1-300x115.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-16.1-768x294.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-16.1-1536x589.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-16.1-2048x785.jpg 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2000px) 100vw, 2000px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>In our example, the line height is only 1 (100%). Increasing it to 1.6 (160%) helps to improve readability.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1880\" height=\"2000\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-16-1880x2000.jpg\" alt=\"In our example, the line height is changed from 1 (100%) to 1.6 (160%).\" class=\"wp-image-912\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-16-1880x2000.jpg 1880w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-16-282x300.jpg 282w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-16-768x817.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-16-1444x1536.jpg 1444w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-16-1925x2048.jpg 1925w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1880px) 100vw, 1880px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">We fixed&nbsp;it!<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>With a handful of simple but powerful UI design guidelines, we quickly found and fixed a whole bunch of problems with our example design.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1880\" height=\"2000\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-0-1880x2000.jpg\" alt=\"UI design example before and after\" class=\"wp-image-880\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-0-1880x2000.jpg 1880w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-0-282x300.jpg 282w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-0-768x817.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-0-1444x1536.jpg 1444w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/03\/ui-design-tips-0-1925x2048.jpg 1925w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1880px) 100vw, 1880px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>I hope you\u2019re starting to see that UI design doesn\u2019t have to be so hard. It might appear to be a magical art form, but a lot of it is made up from logical rules or guidelines like the ones we just learned. Using objective logic, rather than subjective opinion, makes it faster and easier to design intuitive, accessible, and beautiful interfaces.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"\/>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Want more?<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>These are just a few of the logic-driven guidelines from my <a href=\"https:\/\/www.practical-ui.com\/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">UI design book<\/a>. You\u2019ll find hundreds more with detailed examples in the book.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><a href=\"https:\/\/www.practical-ui.com\/\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"2000\" height=\"993\" src=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/05\/ui-design-book-pages-adham-dannaway-2000x993.jpg\" alt=\"ui design book\" class=\"wp-image-822\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/05\/ui-design-book-pages-adham-dannaway-2000x993.jpg 2000w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/05\/ui-design-book-pages-adham-dannaway-300x149.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/05\/ui-design-book-pages-adham-dannaway-768x381.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/05\/ui-design-book-pages-adham-dannaway-1536x763.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/www.adhamdannaway.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/05\/ui-design-book-pages-adham-dannaway-2048x1017.jpg 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2000px) 100vw, 2000px\" \/><\/a><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>PS If you found this article helpful, share it with others and follow me on <a href=\"https:\/\/www.twitter.com\/AdhamDannaway\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Twitter<\/a> and <a href=\"https:\/\/au.linkedin.com\/in\/adhamdannaway\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">LinkedIn<\/a> for daily design tips, tools, resources, and inspiration.&nbsp;<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p class=\"excerpt\">A UI design case study to redesign an example user interface using logical rules or guidelines<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":913,"comment_sta